Course introduces the student to information fundamental to understanding clinical microbiology principles. Focus will also be an introduction to the principles of antimicrobial therapy, which topic is tightly related to microbial world and infection. Topics addressed include select areas of infections: UTI, respiratory tract infections, STD, hospital infections, GIT infections etc.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The clinical microbiology programme aims to provide the pharmacy students with the basic theoretical foundation necessary for the independent pharmacy' specialist practice in a clinical or outpatients environment and for the lifelong advancement of the subject.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  * Knows the etiology, pathogenesis and treatment principles of microbial infection seen in Estonian clinical practice.
* Knows the range of principal microbiology tests used in the clinical practice to investigate the etiology of infection with different body locations.
* Understand the ways in which hospital infections are managed and prevented.
* Is able to make basic interpretation on microbiology laboratory results in the context of infection.
* Knows clinically useful spectra of antibacterial and antiviral drugs.
* Can interpret the PK/PD data and the results of bacterial susceptibility testing.
* Is able to apply the principles of contemporary antibacterial treatment.
